##After 40 days, I woke up in Wuhan

The papernews

The function introduction, has the connotation the current politics new media

Intern, Zhang Zhuo, reporter of thepaper.cn, Ren Wu

After 40 days in Wuhan, Kenneth Chan Yan felt like he was "in jail" every day.

Wearing the same pajamas she left Xianning in 40 days ago, Kenneth Chan Yan's four and a half month old daughter, who had a fever of 40.7 degrees, drove to the hospital with her husband and mother in their pajamas. First went to the home Xianning Jiayu County Hospital, did a check-up, the doctor said it may be encephalitis, the proposal sent to Wuhan immediately for consultation.

It never occurred to Kenneth Chan Yan that he would be stranded in Wuhan, where he was supposed to be seeking medical care, and that he might have ended up on the street. A daughter WHO's still recovering, a father who's sick at home.

Kenneth Chan Yan and other migrants stranded in Wuhan gathered in a crowd of 500 people and shared a common desire: to go home.

"City closing" time

These "stranded" people entered Wuhan before the closure of the city for various reasons, some came to see a doctor, some came to visit relatives, others came to travel, others got off the wrong highway after the closure of the city and were trapped here, they were all anxiously awaiting the day of their departure.

On January 17, Liang Xiuwen, who was in Jiangmen, Guangdong Province, set off to visit his family in Wuhan. Sister-in-law's family in Wuhan, years ago sister returned to Wuhan to prepare a second child. Liang Xiuwen wants to bring his parents and children to visit his sister. He drives his sister's eldest son, who is studying in Guangdong Province.

Before setting out, Liang xiuwen sees the news about Wuhan"pneumonia of unknown cause", a bit worried, call and elder sister to ask a situation. Sister said, "the news has been announced, said rumors, has put a few people arrested, it's okay, we are all okay. ". Sister repeatedly said nothing, to eliminate the heart of Liang xiuwen worries.

Just came to Wuhan, because sister lives in the countryside, so also did not feel the strain of the epidemic, "come to see or before, no change. ".

The day before the city was closed, her sister's second child was born, her brother-in-law's family came, and all three families were delighted with the new arrival. A large family gathered together, very lively, not new year, has begun to have a taste.
On the morning of the 23rd, Liang Xiuwen woke up to the news that the city had been closed at 10 o'clock. Only then did she realize that the outbreak might be unusual and that it had reached the point of closing the city. She began to panic a little, talk to the family about leaving while there's still time.

"We were discussing that it shouldn't be too long, and we were going to be here for the New Year, " she recalled. "It was embarrassing to leave just a few days after we arrived. ". So Liang and his family stayed behind.

At this time, Wuhan Maternal and Child Health Care Hospital, Kenneth Chan Yan and her mother, husband, is in the ward with their four and a half month old baby. They watched as the rest of the family moved away from the four-patient Ward until they were the only ones left.

Before going to Wuhan, Kenneth Chan Yan and her husband had also been following the epidemic on Weibo, but had not yet said "human-to-human transmission" . "We thought it was probably just like swine flu, and rushed to Wuhan without thinking so much. ".

On January 20, Kenneth Chan Yan's daughter was diagnosed with sepsis at the Wuhan Maternal and Child Health Hospital and was admitted to the ICU, where she was expected to undergo a lumbar puncture.

On the morning of the siege, the mother of a child in the next bed urged the nurses to finish their injections and say they had to get out of town by ten. Kenneth Chan Yan recalls a day when the hospital cleared out some patients, and a two and a half month old baby from the same ward, who had only been out of the ICU for a few days, was persuaded to go home.

A few days earlier, doctors had told Kenneth Chan Yan to get ready for the New Year in the hospital, because her daughter's fever had not yet subsided and she was taking the highest level of antibiotics that required mechanical assistance, which was not available in her home hospital.

Therefore, the news of the closure of the city did not give the Kenneth Chan Yan family too much heart waves, "we think the closure of the city will be a week or two, and then darling is also good, we can go back. ".

Every night, Kenneth Chan Yan and her daughter were crammed into a bed, and her mother sat in a nearby chair. For the first few days, Kenneth Chan Yan's husband slept in a chair in the hallway. After the city was sealed off, the hospital said that only one family member could be left to prevent cross contamination, but Kenneth Chan Yan, who could not take care of his daughter alone, asked his mother to stay with him, the husband went to sleep in the car.
Kenneth Chan Yan and her mother took her into the hallway and carried her around until she fell asleep, then returned to the hospital room. The daughter was still feverish, and she often cried at night.

On New Year's Eve, Kenneth Chan Yan's daughter went to bed after a shot. She thought of her daughter having a lumbar puncture the other day, a long needle sticking into such a small body and pulling out the spinal cord from between the bones.

She could not sleep, and by day it was bright and cheerful, and by night the whole world was grey. Stand up to the window, looking out the window in front of the city that is particularly noisy street, in recent days has become a silence.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Kenneth Chan Yan stands in front of a window on New Year's Eve.

A siege without end

Kenneth Chan Yan felt as if ten years had passed since the siege.

On Jan. 29, doctors spoke to Kenneth Chan Yan and suggested she take her daughter home. Kenneth Chan Yan wondered, shouldn't we wait for the antibiotics to degrade? Doctors implicitly expressed that staying in the hospital might be more dangerous, leaving them to weigh in.

They were on a floor where a child had contracted pneumonia, and Kenneth Chan Yan and her husband talked about discharging their daughter.

The next day, Kenneth Chan Yan left the hospital with her daughter, who was still in an unstable condition. The four of them were in trouble again -- "without a home in Wuhan, where shall we live? "

She called a lot of hotels, and none of them would take her calls. Kenneth Chan Yan called for help, hoping to explain what had happened and apply to leave Wuhan for home. She called the Mayor Hotline, the Transportation Authority to the CDC, the community, help stations... call the past, the other side will always give her the next call, a circle down and back to the origin, "you call the Mayor Hotline to ask. ".

Kenneth Chan Yan looked at her feverish baby and thought it would be all right if she went through it alone, but darling was so young. "If I keep this up for another two days, I'll be wandering the streets with my baby... how can I, help me? " Kenneth Chan Yan tweeted helplessly.

On the night of their release, the Kenneth Chan Yan spent the night making up in their car. The next day, a friend saw her tweet, saying that her house was empty and that a spare key was under the door mat for the Kenneth Chan Yan family.

Finally, a place to live, but the problems just keep coming. One Night, Kenneth Chan Yan's father had a heart attack at home alone and sent her a message saying he couldn't move and his head was wooden. Kenneth Chan Yan called 120 for his father, but after the community checked in and heard that Kenneth Chan Yan's father had returned from Guangzhou, he left.

That night, Kenneth Chan Yan was afraid to hang up on his father, saying a few words now and then to make sure he was okay. Kenneth Chan Yan didn't hang up until his father took the medicine and said he was feeling better and sleepy.

More anxious than Kenneth Chan Yan to get home was her mother, her ailing father on one side, and her ailing grandfather on the other. My mother couldn't sleep at night. "She sat there like an owl, " she would sit there in a daze for half a day.

My grandfather had a heart bypass years ago and recently had a heart attack and was on oxygen at home. Kenneth Chan Yan's mother was afraid to let them go to the hospital alone. She was crying while she was on the phone with her grandmother. Kenneth Chan Yan wanted to cry too, but she couldn't stop herself from crying, so she bit her lip to keep it in.

These days, grandma and GRANDPA rely on neighbors to "feed" , upstairs and downstairs who have more food to grandma and GRANDPA door put a little, knock on the door on the left.

Kenneth Chan Yan said she could have taken care of darling and her father if she could have been with her family, and her mother could have taken care of her grandparents, but now that we're so far apart, it's hard to be together.

Liang Xiuwen also more and more flustered. The first thing she does when she wakes up in the morning is to look at the real time data of the outbreak. Her heart is gripped by a multiplying number of infections, and her anxiety is growing exponentially. Two days ago, Liang Xiuwen had a dream that he had cycled back to his home in Jiangmen. But when I woke up, I was still in Wuhan.

My five-year-old daughter was happy when she first arrived, hanging out with a few of her relatives'children. Recently, began to play tired, coupled with the lack of fruit and vegetables at home, the daughter cried for a long time did not eat meat, but also want to eat grapefruit, always chasing her to ask, "mom, when can we go home? "

Three families and a dozen people eat together every day. The table can not sit, can only eat in batches, the elderly children eat first, the rest of the people eat. Liang xiuwen is also embarrassed to eat more everyday, feel oneself a family of five live in elder sister-in-law family to add a lot of trouble.

"If you look at such a large family, we'll eat them all up, and now it's hard to buy things. " The village is under control, and only the boss of the village commissary can go out every few days to buy goods, to provide for the people of the village. "Most of the vegetables are 20 yuan a catty, even the potatoes are seven or eight yuan a catty. "

On the other hand, can not go back this month more than a month, rent, wages and loan repayment, Liang Xiuwen spent more than 50,000, "If I do not go back to bankruptcy. ".

On February 20, the Jiangmen government lifted restrictions on people coming to Jiangmen from key epidemic areas and gradually resumed work. Liang xiuwen heard other at home do self-employed friends are one after another to start business, she more anxious.

The struggle in the city

Huang Liang is Hubei Xiaogan people, to Wuhan for three years, he worked as a construction worker, also did temporary security. Originally planned to go home on the 23rd, because Wuhan is close to home, Huang Liang home tickets are bought as you go. January 23, he woke up at 11:00, saw the news push only to know that the "closed city" , can not go back.

More frightening to Huang Liang than not being able to go home, is not being able to go out and make money. Originally there is no one to do a number of temporary workers, hands are not too much savings, if the "city" closed for a long time, they may not be able to go on.

On the fifth day of the first lunar month, Huang Liang lived in a small area where a friend said the thunder God mountain side is looking for temporary workers, Huang Liang is worried about where to find some living to earn money, so he went to the thunder God mountain with a friend.

It was really People Mountain People Sea, he recalls, on the two days he went to work. He looked at the crowds and wondered why the government had closed the shops, called on residents to be quarantined, not to congregate, the streets were empty, but there were so many people on the construction site, so close to each other?

Working eight or nine hours a day, Huang Liang said is not very tired, "many people AH, all by people piled up. ". The two days he worked at Thor Mountain were the best two days Huang Liang had eaten since the siege.

After two days, the thunder God mountain side said that does not need the temporary worker, Huang Liang has lost his job again.

Wang Tianming, 28, came to Wuhan after the city was closed in order to return early to make money.

His home is in Tianmen, more than 100 kilometers from Wuhan, where he has spent the past year as a crowdsourced courier rider. On January 10, the House he rented in Wuhan expired, and he went home for the Lunar New Year.

After the New Year, he could not hold back at home, thinking of returning to Wuhan delivery, May this period of delivery less, he can earn more. "At that time a lot of places are not clear information, as if it is not so terrible now, they came back. ".

Although the city had been "closed" , but there is no restriction on entering the city. On February 1, he hitchhiked back to Wuhan with a friend.

But when he arrived in Wuhan, Wang found that the situation was completely different from what he had imagined. After getting off the bus, he went to look for his electric car and found it was gone. And then we went back to the place we rented before, and the owner said we couldn't renew the lease.

He checked into a hotel near the Hankou Railway Station for 50 yuan a day, within his means. That day, after checking into the hotel, he went to the supermarket to buy food, just out of the supermarket, saw a 50-year-old man in the next dumpster, the man said, "now there is no food in the trash can. ". Feeling sorry for himself, he handed over the package of food he had just bought. The man said, "thank you, I haven't eaten for several days, " Wang Tianming turned back to the supermarket and bought a new pack for himself.

He tried again to rent a house on the top of the egg shell, but all failed. By February 23, Wang had spent all his 4,000 yuan and decided to walk home.

Over the years, Wang Tianming was accustomed to the outside world. At 16, he dropped out of school to work in Guangdong Province. He had escaped from the Black Brick factory in Dongguan and walked to Huizhou, so he thought it would be easy to return from Wuhan. Early check out of the room, Wang Tianming on the way home.

Back to square one

Wang Tianming calls his behavior of walking home "charging" .

"there were a lot of checkpoints along the way, and I went around them and took a path out of the fields, " he said. After a mobike and a foot relay, he reached the wuhan-Hanchuan border in the evening, near the Han River bridge.

Here he met another hurdle. Next to the checkpoint was the river. He walked two kilometers around the river, trying to find another route, but found that if he wanted to go around the checkpoint, he had to cross the river.

So, Wang Tianming back to the river, want to swim over, he took a few clothes are lost, standing in the river to think about what to do. At this time, the auxiliary police on duty on the bridge saw him and shouted to ask him what to do.

Auxiliary police asked the situation of Wang Tianming and then called the police. Subsequently, the new ditch police station to take him to the hospital for a medical examination, the test results showed normal, the police said to send him to the aid station, but Wang Tianming refused. "When I was in Guangdong, I used to go to the aid station. When I got there, they took away all your things. It was not free. " So he didn't want to go.

It was a little after 11 p.m. , and Wang Tianming wandered the streets for a while, not knowing where to go. His phone wasn't working, and he couldn't call anyone else, so he just... dialed 110 again. At about 1 am on February 24, the police of Sandian police station sent Wang Tianming to a settlement.

"Oh, I failed to charge, " Wang said. What really persuaded him to stop was the words of the auxiliary police at the river. "Even if you did swim through, you still have dozens of checkpoints to go through. " Wang thought so, too, today walked for a long time do not know how many checkpoints, every time to go around, really too difficult.
Wang Tianming thus returned to the original point.

On February 24, "Wuhan Publication" issued two circulars, first in the "17 notice" mentioned that "stranded in the Han people can leave the city. Only three and a half hours after the announcement, "Wuhan Publication" issued a "New Wuhan Pneumonia Epidemic Prevention and control headquarters notice" (No. 18) , declared the morning issued "notice 17" invalid.

For three and a half hours, the mood of all the migrants stranded in Wuhan was like a roller coaster.

Liang said he felt as if he had won the lottery when he saw the notice on the 17th this morning. When he saw the notice on the 18th, it looked like he was cashing in his winnings. He was told that the ticket had expired.

She is not reconciled, and call the prevention and Control Headquarters, advisory can not open the permit back in the name of the husband fire unit, or not feasible. She gave up, put the packed luggage one by one out, can only and wechat group friends cheer each other. She sent a photo of Magnolia flowers at the door, and the group voice said, "look at the flowers, the mood will be better. ".

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Magnolia flowers shared by Liang Xiuwen in the group.

Kenneth Chan Yan wasn't surprised when she saw the 18th announcement, and she said she wasn't surprised by how things turned out after all that time.

When Darling left the house, just over four and a half months ago, she had grown two lower front teeth, and Kenneth Chan Yan said seeing darling's tiny white teeth was the happiest she had seen in 40 days.

Huang said that even if the seal was lifted tomorrow, he should still be able to stay and find some work to earn money and not be in a hurry to go back. The rent is five days late, and I haven't eaten that much meat or vegetables since I got back from working at Thor Mountain.

On February 27, Wuhan released the rescue channel for stranded people outside the city of Han. A friend who knew Huang Liang's difficulties forwarded the link to let him fill out an application and try it out.

On that day, the street sent Huang Liang some turnips and cabbages, Huang Liang said he had been very satisfied, he said more difficult than his people must have a lot. "I'm just going to have some food, and I'm going to try to stay alive, " he said. "when the epidemic is over, I'm going to be on my own. "
